ire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Isham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Northamptonshire): habitational name from Isham, Northamptonshire. See   Isom  , compare   Esham  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Esham","meanings":["English: variant of   Isham  . This surname is no longer found in Britain.","History: The name is first recorded in Northamton County, VA, when Daniel Esham came over as an indentured servant in 1651."]},{"name":"Isom","meanings":["English (Essex): habitational name from Isham in Northamptonshire. The placename is derived from the river name <i>Ise</i> (of Celtic origin) + Old English <i>hām</i> ‘homestead’."]},{"name":"Ishman","meanings":["English: possibly an altered form of   Isham  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":9,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Isham was born in 1373, in Pytchley, Northamptonshire, England, his father, Robert de Isham, was 26 and his mother, Julian, was 20. He married Julianna Bradfield in 1390, in Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 31 March 1424, in his hometown, at the age of 51, and was buried in Pytchley, Northamptonshire, England."},"et":{"1373–31 March 1424":"1373–31. märts 1424","1373–1424":"1373–1424","1370–1430":"1370–1430","1402–1475":"1402–1475","1348–1424":"1348–1424","1353–1377":"1353–1377","October 2014":"oktoober 2014","1373":"1373","13 Mar 1424":"13. märts 1424","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1390":"1390","April 1424":"aprill 1424","1348":"1348","1402":"1402","1424":"1424","31 March 1424":"31. märts 1424","1377":"1377","1475":"1475","1353":"1353","1430":"1430","17 April 1412":"17 aprill 1412","2 March 1402":"2. märts 1402","Rose Manor, Pytchley, Northampton, England":"Pytchley, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Rose Manor, Pytchley, Northamptonshire, England":"Pytchley, Northamptonshire, England","Pytchley, Northamptonshire, England":"Pytchley, Northamptonshire, England","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1373–31 March 1424":"1373–31. maaliskuuta 1424","1373–1424":"1373–1424","1370–1430":"1370–1430","1402–1475":"1402–1475","1348–1424":"1348–1424","1353–1377":"1353–1377","October 2014":"lokakuu 2014","1373":"1373","13 Mar 1424":"13. maaliskuuta 1424","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1390":"1390","April 1424":"huhtikuu 1424","1348":"1348","1402":"1402","1424":"1424","31 March 1424":"31. maaliskuuta 1424","1377":"1377","1475":"1475","1353":"1353",